<subSubSection id="510F9C83641F48E68DFA206632156F2F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="note">
<paragraph id="938355A1E307507FD5D84F4F9B0A1EA8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The lunule of 
<taxonomicName id="EE2CCAE2D4114096B748E2759DE2D454" authority="Hendel, 1931" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Poemyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poemyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7D4FCD311F58CA4B3DBBA329887FD444" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Poemyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterised as being relatively high and narrow, often being much higher than wide. This is exaggerated in many species where the fronto-orbital plate is produced over the 
<normalizedToken id="640FE62D0F3834E975ABA417781D1500" originalValue="lunule’s">lunule's</normalizedToken>
wider base. Some species, such as 
<taxonomicName id="AE126E1B8C1783575299972DE07886DF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. inconspicua" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="inconspicua">
<emphasis id="312A90707C7FB1ABADA6243A9A271746" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. inconspicua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Malloch), however, have a shorter lunule similar to that of species in the 
<taxonomicName id="874412864083A9A8E1083387310B20C1" authority="Butomomyza" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="(Butomomyza) subsp. subgenus" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subGenus" species="inconspicua" subGenus="Butomomyza" subSpecies="subgenus">subgenus Butomomyza</taxonomicName>
, but the texture of the lunule in 
<taxonomicName id="80F9D60F077FA67A678B9D346199CD94" authority="Hendel, 1931" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Poemyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poemyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A45A04F24D95ABCDBABBC8AA06962E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Poemyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species is pitted and bare (not flat and velvety) and the acrostichal seta is usually absent (not present). The buccal cavity between the arms of the clypeus is also densely covered with minute spicules, at least in Nearctic species, but this has not yet been confirmed for the global fauna. A similar lunule is seen in 
<taxonomicName id="26BBB7FBE399E6F745F7EC9ABA566033" authority="Frey, 1946" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenophytomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="04E30EFE7BEC66E6CABEDA59DB49AF3E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has a pointed first flagellomere similar to some 
<taxonomicName id="5E97CF636DA39A20E9CA1D4E039426CC" authority="Hendel, 1931" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Poemyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poemyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="525E3DBADD05B4A7A18973028CB93586" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Poemyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName id="48A332552D94B52AA3005054B9EFB21B" authority="Frey, 1946" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenophytomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="812AD5969B8B17B17D128DF40C3CFB2B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in lacking lateral scutellar setae.
</paragraph>
